Auto loader — directory listing versus file notification mode.

Auto loader has two ways to discover new files, and the choice is a cost-and-scale trade-off.

Directory listing mode is the default. On every micro-batch, auto loader lists the source directory and figures out which files are new. It needs no extra cloud setup, which makes it simple to start with. But once a prefix holds hundreds of millions or billions of files, listing the directory every batch becomes the bottleneck.

File notification mode flips that around. Auto loader sets up a notification on the cloud storage — using the cloud's own queue service — so that whenever an object is created, an event is pushed onto a queue. Auto loader just reads the queue instead of scanning the directory. It costs a little more setup and a few cloud resources, but it scales to enormous file counts because discovery no longer depends on how many files already exist.

So the rule is simple. Start with directory listing. Switch to file notification when listing becomes too slow at very large scale.
